comment: Finds a Human working for an Employer, and managing a Process that has no  operator.

label: IcP
comment: Finds a Process controlling an Internet class subnet.

label: InternetMP
comment: Finds an Internet class network.

label: IpH
comment: Finds a Host providing an Internet class subnet.

label: LnSuP-H
comment: Finds a login service using a process where the two do not have the same Host.

label: LS
comment: Finds a solo Logical Subnet.

label: LS-iH
comment: Finds a solo Logical Subnet.

label: LS-prH
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet not provided by any host.

label: LS-S
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet that is not abstract, but is accessible from no physical space.

label: MHC
comment: Finds a solo Mobile Console Host.

label: MHcIS
comment: Finds a Mobile Console Host in a Public Space connected to the Internet.

label: MHHS
comment: Finds a Host whose physical host is a Mobile Console Host in a Space, where it can access at least one Logical Subnet (this pattern contains only multiple network access contexts), plus optionally an interactive user and system manager.

label: PccP
comment: Finds two processes, each of which controls the other. This is the simplest case of a cyclic authentication dependency, which is a logical impossibility.

label: PC-LnS
comment: Finds a physical Cluster that is not controlled by any process.

label: PCPHLSS
comment: Finds a Process location access context and the related process, host and space and one related subnet.

label: PcWH
comment: Finds a WiFiLAN and its local implementation, plus a controlling process.

label: PH
comment: Finds a solo physical host, and optionally its manager.

label: PH2
comment: Finds a process with two distinct hosts.

label: PH2dS
comment: Finds a physical host located in two different spaces.

label: PHdH
comment: Finds a host that has a physical host (but is not the physical host).

label: PHHPS
comment: Finds a process running on a host that can be accessed from a space.

label: PHHS
comment: Finds a host that directly is or indirectly has a physical host in a space, and all connected logical subnets accessible from that space.

label: PHLSS
comment: Finds a host that has or directly is a physical host in a space and is connected to a logical subnet accessible from that space (other than an abstract hotspot).

label: PHS
comment: Finds a Physical Host located in a Space, and optionally the host manager and interactive user.

label: PH-S
comment: Finds a physical host that is not located in any space.

label: PHS-iC
comment: Finds a Physical Host that is not a Cluster located in a Space, and optionally the host manager and interactive user.

label: PHS-iP
comment: Finds a Physical Host that is not a Personal Device located in a Space, and optionally the host manager and interactive user.

label: PMHHS
comment: Finds a non-trivial Process running on a host whose physical host is a Mobile Console Host that may be located in a Space, plus associated process network access contexts from that Space, and optionally an interactive Process user.

label: PnH
comment: Finds a Process with no Host.

label: PS-iH
comment: Finds a solo Physical Subnet that is not a hotspot.

label: RAC
comment: Finds a remote access client.

label: RACuHRASP-iPL
comment: Finds a host running a process that is not a reverse proxy or a remote access service, and a remote access service that uses the process, and is used by a remote access client.

label: RACuP-iP
comment: Finds a Remote Access Client using a Process that is not a reverse proxy.

label: RACuRHRASP-iPL
comment: Finds a host running a process that is not a reverse proxy or a remote access service, and a remote access service that uses the process, where both are used remotely by a remote access client.

label: RAS
comment: Finds a remote access service.

label: Rr
comment: Finds a solo Router.

label: Rr-LnS
comment: Finds a Router that is not controlled by any process.

label: RSSH
comment: Finds a Radio Subnet provided by a Gateway Host accessible from a Space, and optionally the service controlling access to it and the gateway manager.

label: RSS-HP
comment: Finds a Radio Subnet accessible from a Space, and the subnet it implements locally, where there is no gateway specified as the subnet provider and no controlling Process.

label: RSSH-P
comment: Finds a Radio Subnet with no controlling process, provided by a Gateway host and accessible from a Space, plus optionally the manager of the Gateway.

label: RTuHP-iPL-RAS
comment: Finds a Host running a Process that is neither a remote access service nor a reverse proxy, but is used remotely by a Remote Terminal client, not mediated by a collocated remote access service, nor by a reverse proxy.

label: RTuP-hCLI
comment: Finds a Remote Terminal that uses a Process that has no CLI and is not a remote access service nor a proxy, plus the Process host.

label: RTurP-hCLI
comment: Finds a Remote Terminal that remotely uses a Process that has no CLI and is not a remote access service nor a proxy, plus the Process host.

label: RTuRTuS-uR
comment: Finds a remote terminal using remotely another remote terminal which is using remotely a third process that is not yet remotely used by the first.

label: SH
comment: Finds a Shell Host (i.e. a host that allows user commands with the rights of the administrator or some user/process).

label: SHAC
comment: Finds a Shell Host plus optionally its manager, and an associated access context.

label: SHACPmAC
comment: Finds a process running on a shell host in a space and the host location access context, with all related process location and network access contexts where the host is normally in that location or connected to that network.

label: SHGP
comment: Finds a simple host running a general process.

label: SHLnSACPmAC
comment: Finds a remote access service controlling a process running on a shell host in a space, and a location access context to the remote access service, related process access contexts and optionally the process manager.

label: SHmACPAC
comment: Finds a process running on a shell host in a space, and a location access context to the process, related host access contexts and optionally the host manager.

label: SHmACRLnSAC
comment: Finds a remote access service controlling a shell host in a space, and a location access context to the process, related host access contexts and optionally the host manager.

label: SH-mHu
comment: Finds a Shell Host that has no manager.

label: SHP
comment: Finds a Process running on a shell Host, and optionally the interactive process user and host manager.

label: SHP-iT
comment: Finds a non-trivial Process running on a shell Host, and optionally the interactive process user and host manager.

label: SHuPH-Hu
comment: Finds a Human managing a Space in which an unmanaged Fixed Host is located.

label: StDC
comment: Finds a stakeholder operating a data centre.

label: StH
comment: Finds a stakeholder operating a Host.

label: StHP
comment: Finds a Stakeholder operating a Host that runs a Process.

label: StSPH-St
comment: Finds a Private Space operated by a Stakeholder where a Fixed Host with no operator is located.

label: StS-St
comment: Finds a Private Space operated by a Stakeholder where access is not controlled by any stakeholder.

label: Sv-LnS
comment: Finds a Server that is not controlled by any process.

label: TH
comment: Finds a solo trivial host, and optionally the host manager, an interactive user, and any related access contexts.

label: THGP
comment: Finds a trivial host running a general process.

label: TP
comment: Finds a solo trivial process.

label: WHmWS
comment: Finds a WiFi hotspot with at least one local implementation.

label: WiFiSSoH
comment: Finds a WiFi subnet accessible from a Space, the network it implements, and optionally the host providing the subnet and service controlling access to it.

label: WmPH
comment: Finds a solo World asset (i.e. the inferred global public space), in which at least one Host is assumed to be (due to having no other defined location).

label: WpHS-aF
comment: Finds a mobile host or virtual host running on it, in a space, providing a WiFi LAN which is not accessible from any space, and providing no other WiFiLAN accessible in its space.

label: WpHSH-aF
comment: Finds a mobile host or virtual host running on it, in a space, providing a WiFi LAN which is a hotspot, and no other WiFiLAN accessible in its space.

label: WS-H
comment: Finds a solo WiFiLAN that is not an abstract hotspot.

label: WSSH
comment: Finds a Wired Subnet provided by a Gateway host accessible from a Space, and optionally the process controlling access and the manager of the gateway.

label: WSS-HP
comment: Finds a Wired Subnet accessible from a Space, where there is no gateway specified as the subnet provider, and no controlling Process.

label: WSSH-P
comment: Finds a Wired Subnet with no controlling process, provided by a Gateway host accessible from a Space, and optionally the manager of the Gateway.

label: DDoH
comment: Change from: Finds an open network path from the Internet to (but not via) a Host connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface and access context, plus the location contexts for the host being on that subnet, and optionally the host manager.

label: GdHRS
comment: Finds a gateway providing a radio subnet to which a distinct host is connected, and optionally a process controlling access to the radio subnet, which in this case implements an abstract network (hotspot or cellular network), i.e. there is an implements relationship to a distinct abstract subnet.

label: GdHRSi
comment: Finds a gateway providing a radio subnet to which a distinct host is connected, and optionally a process controlling access to the radio subnet, which in this case does not implement a separate abstract network (hotspot or cellular network), i.e. it has a self-referential implements relationship.

label: GdHWS
comment: Finds a gateway providing a wired subnet to which a distinct host is connected, and optionally a process controlling access to the subnet.

label: HIoH
comment: Finds a Host connected to the Internet, and the associated network Interface, plus optionally the host manager.

label: HLoH
comment: Finds a Host with optional system manager, connected to a Layer 2 Logical Subnet, and the associated network Interface, and a second, distinct host on the same subnet.

label: HRoH
comment: Finds a Host with optional system manager, connected to a Layer 3 Logical Subnet (but not the Internet), and the associated network Interface, and a second, remote host on the same subnet.

label: HRSGSoS
comment: Finds a host connecting to a radio subnet, a gateway host located in a space that is providing the radio subnet, and optionally a service that controls access to the radio subnet.

label: HSRSoGS
comment: Finds a host located in a space connecting to a radio subnet, plus optionally the controlling host and service for the subnet.

label: HSWSoGS
comment: Finds a host located in a space connecting to a wired subnet it does not provide, plus optionally the host manager, and the gateway and service controlling the subnet.

label: HWSGSoS
comment: Finds a host connecting to a wired network it does not provide, a gateway host located in a space that is providing the network, and optionally the gateway host manager, and a service that controls access to the network.

label: I
comment: Finds a solo Interface, plus the associated host and subnet and optionally the host manager.

label: ILSA
comment: Finds an Interface connecting to a Logical Subnet that implements an Abstract Subnet that is not the same as the Logical Subnet.

label: INC
comment: Finds a solo Interface, plus the associated host, subnet, and a host network access context where the interface is connected.

label: IoH
comment: Finds an open network path from the Internet to (but not via) a Host connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface and access context, plus the location contexts for the host being on that subnet, and optionally the host manager.

label: L3c-rGc-rL3
comment: Finds a Host connected from an IP subnet to a second distinct IP subnet, both in the same space, where neither is a hotspot and neither is provided by the gateway.

label: L3c-rGrL3
comment: Finds a Host connected from an IP subnet it does not provide to a second, distinct IP subnet that is provided by the Host, both in the same space, where neither subnet is a hotspot, and there is no logical segment representing the route between subnets via the host..

label: L3rGc-rL3
comment: Finds a Host connected from an IP subnet it provides to a second, distinct IP subnet that it does not provide, both in the same space, where neither subnet is a hotspot.

label: L3rGrL3
comment: Finds a Host providing two IP subnets both in the same space, where there is no logical segment representing the route between subnets via the host.

label: L3SSg2
comment: Finds a gateway from an IP subnet to a distinct IP subnet, along with the forward and (open) return path segments via the gateway.

label: L3SSg2+b
comment: Finds a gateway from one IP subnet to a second IP subnet, along with the segment asset representing the route via the gateway, where this route is blocked by default.

label: L3SSg2AC
comment: Finds a gateway from an IP subnet to a distinct IP subnet, along with the forward and (open) return path segments via the gateway, and a context in which the gateway is connected to both subnets.

label: L3SSg2AC-b
comment: Finds a gateway from one IP subnet to an IP subnet, along with the segment asset representing the route via the gateway, and a context in which the gateway is connected to both subnets, where this route is not blocked by default.

label: L3SSg2-b
comment: Finds a gateway from one IP subnet to a second IP subnet, along with the segment asset representing the route via the gateway, where this route is not blocked by default.

label: LoH
comment: Finds a Host in a context where it is connected to a Layer 2 Logical Subnet, and the associated network interface, plus all contexts where it is connected to the same subnet (there may be others), and optionally the host manager.

label: LPLS2NSg2
comment: Finds a route between subnets through a gateway where NAT is used on the return path, and a logical path traversing the forward segment.

label: LPsLS
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet at the start of a Logical Path.

label: NoH
comment: Finds an open network path not via the Internet from a remote attacker subnet to (but not via) a Host connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface and access context, plus the location contexts for the host being on that subnet, and optionally the host manager.

label: NP2LS
comment: Finds a network path with a subpath that visits a subnet.

label: NP2LSg
comment: Finds a network path with a subpath that traverses a logical segment.

label: NP3
comment: Finds a Network Path with a subpath that extends a third path, which does not itself have a subpath relationship to the first.

label: NPLS
comment: Finds a Network Path that starts and ends on the same subnet, i.e. it uses no gateways.

label: NPmLSmSg
comment: Finds a Network Path that traverses at least one Logical Segment, plus the Logical Subnet(s) it visits (in this pattern there should be more than one).

label: OPLS1
comment: Finds a zero-length Logical Path and a Path Terminator (NPE) to a Logical Subnet, where there is a Logical Route via a Gateway Host to the Subnet from some other Logical Subnet.

label: OPLS2
comment: Finds a Network Path and terminator (NPE) to a destination Logical Subnet, where there is a Logical Route into the Subnet at the start of the Path via a Gateway, from a Subnet not visited by any shorter path to the destination, where the Path is routed via at least one Host but not via the Gateway.

label: OPPS1
comment: Finds a zero-length Physical Path and a Path Terminator (PPE) to a Physical Subnet, where there is a Logical Route via a Physical Gateway Host to the Subnet from some other Physical Subnet.

label: OPPS2
comment: Finds a Physical Path and terminator (PPE) to a destination Physical Subnet, where there is a Logical Route into the Subnet at the start of the Path via a Gateway, from a Physical Subnet not visited by any shorter physical path to the destination, where the Path is routed via at least one Host but not via the Gateway.

label: RIoH
comment: Finds an open network path to the Internet from (but not via) a Host connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface and access context, plus the location contexts for the host being on that subnet, and optionally the host manager.

label: RNoH
comment: Finds an open network path not via the Internet to a remote attacker subnet from (but not via) a Host connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface and access context, plus the location contexts for the host being on that subnet, and optionally the host manager.

label: RoH
comment: Finds an open network path from a remote attacker L3 subnet to (and not via) a Host in a space connected to a local subnet, and the associated network interface, plus the contexts in which the host is so connected (there must be at least one), and optionally the host manager.

label: RScGcRS
comment: Finds a Physical Host connected between two distinct WiFi subnets, both in the same space.

label: Sg
comment: Finds a gateway host between two subnets, plus the logical segments representing routes between the subnets via this gateway.

label: SgHfILS
comment: Finds a Logical Segment via a Host routing from a Logical Subnet, and the Interface between the Host and Logical Subnet.

label: SgHtILS
comment: Finds a Logical Segment via a Host routing to a Logical Subnet, and the Interface between the Host and Logical Subnet.

label: WScMcWS
comment: Finds a Mobile Host connected between two distinct Wired LANs, both in the same space.

label: HuaSaE
comment: Finds a human with access to a space that is accessible from a public entrance space.

label: HuPSoSt
comment: Finds a Human with access to a Private Space, and an optional employer of the Human.

label: HuPSSt
comment: Finds a Human with access to a Private Space, and their employer.

label: PPS
comment: Finds a Private Physical Space.

label: PPS-E
comment: Finds a Private Space that is not accessible from any other Space.

label: PScSt
comment: Finds a private space controlled by a stakeholder.

label: PSS
comment: Finds two spaces, one of which is private and accessible via the other.

label: DHuDC
comment: Finds a data asset relating to a human along with a stored copy of the data.

label: DHuDF
comment: Finds a data asset relating to a human along with a flowing copy of the data.

label: D-Hu-Th
comment: Finds a solo Data asset which is not spam, not created by a Sensor or stored on an IoT Thing, and does not relate to a human subject.

label: H-Hu
comment: Finds a Host that has no interactive user, no manager, and does not relate to any user.

label: Hs
comment: Finds a solo Health Sensor.

label: Hu-aDPoS-i
comment: Finds Stakeholder operating a Process that is using Data relating to a Human data subject who may be a child via a controlling Service, where the subject operates the Service but not the Process.

label: Hu-aDPS-io
comment: Finds a Stakeholder operating a Process that is using Data relating to a Human data subject who may be a child via a controlling Service, where the subject does not operate either the Process or the controlling Service.

label: HuDPoS-i
comment: Finds Stakeholder operating a Process that is using Data relating to a Human data subject via a controlling Service, where the subject operates the Service but not the Process.

label: HuDPS-io
comment: Finds a Stakeholder operating a Process that is using Data relating to a Human data subject via a controlling Service, where the subject does not operate either the Process or the controlling Service.

label: HurH-StSt
comment: Finds a Human who does not work for anyone else, with a related personal device that has no operator.

label: HurSesD-Rel
comment: Finds Data produced as output by a Sensor related to a Human, where the data has not been inferred or asserted to be related to the Human.

label: HurThcD-Rel
comment: Finds control input to an IoT Thing related to a Human, where the data has not been inferred or asserted to be related to the Human.

label: HurTh-S-m
comment: Finds a Thing relating to a Human, plus onboard data and processing, where there is no manager and no specified location.

label: HuwStrH-St
comment: Finds a Human working for an Employer, with a personal device that has no other operator.

label: IoT-Hu
comment: Finds a solo IoT Thing that does not relate to a Human data subject. Not used at present, but reserved for a future extension.

label: ACDF-VCS-i
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, that goes via a client and thence a service, plus any data fields, and the related channel, where the connection is direct and not via any credential-sharing intermediaries.

label: ACDF-VFS-i
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault flowing from a service to/via a client, plus any data fields, and the associated channel, where the connection is direct.

label: ACDFVFS-i
comment: Finds a data flow encrypted with keys from a vault flowing from a service to/via a client, plus any data fields, and the associated client channel, where the connection is direct.

label: ACDF-VSC-i
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, that goes via a service and thence a client, and the related channel and any data fields, where the connection is direct and not via any credential-sharing intermediaries.

label: ACDF-VTS-i
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, flowing to a service from/via a client, plus the data, data access and any data fields, and the associated channel, where the connection is direct and not via any credential-sharing intermediaries.

label: ACDFVTS-i
comment: Finds a data flow encrypted with keys from a vault, flowing to a service from/via a client, plus any data fields, the data access, and the associated client channel, where the connection is direct and not via any credential-sharing intermediaries.

label: AC-iDF-VCS
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, that goes via a client and thence a service, plus any data fields, and the related auth channel, where the client and service have a trust relationship w.r.t. the data flow (i.e., they are not intermediaries in an end-to-end relationship).

label: AC-iDFVFC
comment: Finds a data flow encrypted by a key from a vault, flowing from a client to or via a service, and the associated auth channel which must not be to a trust intermediary, the data and data access and any data fields, and process contexts in which the data flows from the client (of which any can cause the threat). The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name (FlowsFrom or Client) in control strategies.

label: AC-iDF-VFC
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted by a key from a vault, flowing from a client to or via a service, and the associated auth channel which must not be to a trust intermediary, the data and data access, any data fields, and process contexts in which the data flows from the client (of which any can cause the threat). The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name (FlowsFrom or Client) in control strategies.

label: AC-iDF-VSC
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, that goes via a service and thence via a client, plus any data fields, and the related auth channel, where the client and service have a trust relationship w.r.t. the data flow (i.e., they are not intermediaries in an end-to-end relationship).

label: AC-iDFVTC
comment: Finds a data flow encrypted by a key from a vault, flowing to a client from or via a service, and the associated auth channel which must not be to a trust intermediary, the data access and any data fields, and process contexts in which the data flows from the client (of which any can cause the threat). The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name (FlowsTo or Client) in control strategies.

label: AC-iDF-VTC
comment: Finds a data flow not encrypted by a key from a vault, flowing to a client from or via a service, and the associated auth channel which must not be to a trust intermediary, the data and data access, and process contexts in which the data flows from the client (of which any can cause the threat). The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name (FlowsTo or Client) in control strategies.

label: APxSCtI
comment: Finds a Service Attack Path starting off a Service Channel, and the path from the attacker subnet which is an extension of the Service Channel path, plus the Interface from the attacker subnet to the first gateway on the Attack Path.

label: CACHcLSS
comment: Finds a service accessed by a client via a subnet the client is on, and an associated context for access to the client, plus the two process hosts and optionally the client user and service manager.

label: CACHLSS
comment: Finds a service that is not acting as a reverse proxy accessed by a client and an associated context for access from the client via a subnet to which it need not normally be connected, plus the two process hosts and optionally the client user and service manager.

label: CAC-pPaAC-pS
comment: Finds a client providing authentication credentials to a process which uses a service to validate those credentials, along with the channels between each pair of processes, where the Client, Process and Service are not in a credential sharing chain.

label: CAC-pPzAC-pS
comment: Finds a client providing indirect authorization credentials to a process which uses a service to validate those credentials, along with the channels between each pair of processes, where the Client, Process and Service are not in a credential sharing chain.

label: CAC-pScAC-pP
comment: Finds a client and process connected via a channel, where the client also uses another service that controls the process, along with the associated channels, where the Client, Process and Service are not in a credential sharing chain.

label: CACSSaS
comment: Finds a channel between a client and a service used to pass authorization tokens, and a second channel from the service to another service used to validate those tokens, along with the hosts of the client and the second service, plus optionally the client user and the managers of the second service and its host.

label: CACSScS
comment: Finds a channel between a client and a service, where authentication on this channel is controlled by authentication on another channel from the same client to a second service, along with the hosts of the client and the second service, plus optionally the client user and the managers of the second service and its host.

label: CACvsCCS
comment: Finds a Client accessing a Service via intermediaries, along with the Auth Channel between the Client and Service, and the related client channels via intermediaries, any of which can cause a threat, plus the client and service hosts and and optionally the service manager and interactive client user.

label: CAPlISAP
comment: Finds a client attack path via a service attack path where the former has a last interface.

label: CAPNPSAP
comment: Finds a Client Attack Path via a Service Attack Path and a Network Path.

label: CAPSAP
comment: Finds a Client Attack Path via a Service Attack Path.

label: CaS-SP
comment: Finds a client that is not a remote access service accessing a service, not via a deputy and not via a shell process on the service host.

label: CCAPNaS
comment: Finds a service and its host accessed by a client via the associated client channel on a closed client attack path from a logical subnet where messages from the attacker come from the same address as those from the client, plus all the associated service process contexts, and optionally the client user and the service and service host managers.

label: CCCCAP
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a proxy Client Channel that goes via an Attack Path.

label: CCCfCCS+aFC
comment: Finds a Client accessing a Service via a Proxy, with the channel between the Client and Service, the channel to the first Proxy, and the client and service hosts, plus a client context in which the client can access the proxy channel.

label: CCCfS+aFC-aI
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the client in which the client can access the channel, and the service cannot be in a context where access to it would be interrupted.

label: CCCfS-aFC
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the client, where the client cannot access the channel in that context.

label: CCCftS+aFC-aTS
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context on each side, where the channel can be accessed from the client in its context, but the service cannot be accessed in its context.

label: CCCLnSAC
comment: Finds a Client and Remote Access Service with a ClientChannel between them, plus their hosts, the contexts for access to the service via the channel, and optionally the client and service managers.

label: CCCmSCS
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a Client Channel between them and all associated Service Channels (of which there must be at least one), plus the client and service hosts and optionally the service manager and interactive client user.

label: CCC-nmCCS
comment: Finds a Client not acting as an authentication proxy with access via at least one proxy to a Service which is not using a separate authenticator, with a Client Channel between them and all associated proxy client channels (of which there must be at least one), plus the client and service hosts and optionally the Client user and Service manager.

label: CCC-nmSCS
comment: Finds a Client accessing and authenticating directly with a Service, the Client Channel between them and all associated Service Channels (of which there must be at least one), plus the client and service hosts and optionally the service manager and client user.

label: CCC-nS
comment: Finds a Client that is not sharing or forwarding credentials, with access to a Service that does not use a separate authenticator, the ClientChannel between them, the Client and Service hosts and optionally the Client user and Service manager.

label: CCC-nS-i
comment: Finds a Client and Service where the Service is responsible for authenticating the client, the ClientChannel between them which must be a direct connection, plus the Client and Service hosts and optionally the Client user and Service manager.

label: CCCPCCS-i
comment: Finds a client accessing a reverse proxy that uses a service, via the associated client channels, where the client and service are not in a credential forwarding chain, plus optionally the reverse proxy manager.

label: CCCS
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a ClientChannel between them, the Client and Service hosts and optionally the client user and the service and service host managers.

label: CCCSAC
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a Client Channel between them, plus their hosts, the contexts for access to the service via the channel, and optionally the client user and service and service host managers.

label: CCCSACvLS
comment: Finds a Client with a Client Channel to a Service via an adjacent L2 subnet, plus their hosts, all related access contexts at the Service, and optionally the client user and the service and service host managers.

label: CCCSCCSDF-Vi
comment: Finds a client accessing a service that uses another service, via the associated client channels, where indirect access by the client is not authenticated by the second service, plus a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, that flows to the second service from the first but not to the client.

label: CCCSCCS-i
comment: Finds a client accessing a service that uses another service, via the associated client channels, where indirect access by the client is not authenticated by the second service.

label: CCCSCSoAC
comment: Finds a Client and Service connected via a Client Channel, also connected by a Service Channel, plus any indirect Auth Channels that depend on this Client Channel (which may be none). The presence of the Service Channel means the first Client Channel is a direct connection (not via intermediaries) involving communication over a network (not via a local API or sockets).

label: CCCSDF-VCCS-i
comment: Finds a client accessing a service that uses another service, via the associated client channels, where indirect access by the client is not authenticated by the second service, plus a data flow and any data fields not encrypted with keys from a vault flowing to the second service from the first but not from the client.

label: CCCS-i
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a direct ClientChannel between them, the Client and Service hosts and optionally the client user and the service and service host managers.

label: CCCS-iAC
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a direct Client Channel between them, plus their hosts, the contexts for access to the service via the channel, and optionally the client user and service and service host managers.

label: CCCSPCCSDF-Vi
comment: Finds a client accessing a proxy that (directly or indirectly) uses a service that uses a second service, where the client is not authenticated by the second service, with a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault going from the second service to the first but not to the client, plus the associated client channels.

label: CCCSPDF-VCCS-i
comment: Finds a client accessing a proxy that (directly or indirectly) uses a service that uses a second service, where the client is not authenticated by the second service, with a data flow not encrypted with keys from a vault, flowing to the second service from the first but not from the client, plus the associated client channels.

label: CCCSPSFCS
comment: Finds a client sending a flow of data to a service via a chain of intermediaries, over which the client communications authentication or authorization credentials.

label: CCCSPSFSC
comment: Finds a client receiving a flow of data from a service via a chain of intermediaries, over which the client communications authentication or authorization credentials.

label: CCCtCCS+aTS
comment: Finds a Client accessing a Service via a Proxy, with the channel between the Client and Service, the channel from the last Proxy, the client and service hosts, and a service context in which the service can be accessed via the proxy channel.

label: CCCvCCS
comment: Finds a Client accessing a Service via a Proxy, with the Client Channel between the Client and Service, and the related channel to the Proxy, the hosts of client and service and and optionally the service manager and interactive client user.

label: CCCvCCvLS
comment: Finds a Client Channel from a Client process that goes via a Logical Subnet and also via another Client Channel (i.e. the client and service communicate via a credential sharing/forwarding chain).

label: CCCvsCC-nS
comment: Finds a Client accessing a Service via intermediaries, where the Service is responsible for client authentication, along with the Client Channel between the Client and Service, and the related channels via intermediaries, any of which can cause a threat, plus the client and service hosts and and optionally the service manager and interactive client user.

label: CCCvsCCSAC
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a Client Channel between them that goes via at least one channel via an intermediary, plus their hosts, the contexts for access to the service via the channel, and optionally the client user and service and service host managers.

label: CCDFCDAScDA-c
comment: Finds a data flow from a service to an indirect client, where the client encrypts the data flow to create an outbound data asset controlled by a vault, which does not control the inbound data flow.

label: CCDFCS
comment: Finds a data flow that goes via a client and thence via a service, plus the related client channel and data.

label: CCDFSC
comment: Finds a data flow that goes via a service and thence a client, and the related  client channel and data.

label: CCDFSDAScDA-c
comment: Finds a data flow to a service from an indirect client, where the service encrypts the data flow to create an outbound data asset controlled by a vault, which does not control the inbound data flow.

label: CCDFSFC
comment: Finds a data flow from a client to/via a service, and the associated client channel, data and the first data step, plus optionally the managers of the service and the source of the data flow. The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name.

label: CCDFSFS
comment: Finds a data flow to/via a client from a service, and the associated client channel, data and the first data step, plus optionally the managers of the service and the source of the data flow. The source of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name.

label: CCDFSTC
comment: Finds a data flow to a client from/via a service, and the associated client channel, data and the last data step, plus optionally the managers of the service and the source of the data flow. The destination of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name.

label: CCDFSTS
comment: Finds a data flow from/via a client to a service, and the associated client channel, data and the last data step, plus optionally the managers of the service and the source of the data flow. The destination of the flow is matched twice, so it can be referred to by either role name.

label: CCDS2FC
comment: Finds a data flowing from/via a client via a service, plus the associated client channel and the data steps from the client and from the service, and optionally the manager of the service and of the data flow source process.

label: CCDS2TC
comment: Finds a data flowing to/via a client via a service, plus the associated client channel and the data steps to the client and to the service, and optionally the manager of the service and of the data flow source process.

label: CCfImSC
comment: Finds a Client Channel from an Interface at the Client host with at least one associated Service Channel.

label: CC-iDFCS
comment: Finds a data flow that goes via a client and thence via a service, plus the related client channel and data, where the client and service have a trust relationship w.r.t. the data flow (i.e., they are not intermediaries in an end-to-end credential sharing chain).

label: CC-iDFC-SS
comment: Finds a data flow that goes via a client and thence via a service, plus the related client channel and data, where the client and service have a trust relationship w.r.t. the data flow (i.e., they are not intermediaries in an end-to-end credential sharing chain), and the client does not get the data from its own client. The last restriction is so related threats are not duplicated if the client also acts as a service when exchanging this data.

label: CC-iDFSC
comment: Finds a data flow that goes via a service and thence via a client, plus the related client channel and data, where the client and service have a trust relationship w.r.t. the data flow (i.e., they are not intermediaries in an end-to-end credential sharing chain).

label: CCSC
comment: Finds a client and service connected by a client channel and a service channel.

label: CCSCAP
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that goes via an Attack Path.

label: CCSCCP
comment: Finds a client channel via a service channel that is via a client path.

label: CCSCfI
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that goes from an Interface.

label: CCSCtI
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that goes to an Interface.

label: CCSCtSg
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that goes via a Logical Segment.

label: CCSCvI
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that goes via an Interface.

label: CCSCvLS
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that visits a Logical Subnet.

label: CCSmDFS
comment: Finds a client and service connected by a client channel, which is used by at least one DataStep representing the possibility to exchange data between the two.

label: CCtImSC
comment: Finds a Client Channel to an Interface at the Service host with at least one associated Service Channel.

label: CDBSC
comment: Finds a process acting as a client to a DB with a Client Channel between them, and optionally the process host manager.

label: CDBSCDSF
comment: Finds a process using data served by a DB service the process is using, and the associated service channel, host and data copy assets, plus optionally the service host manager.

label: CDBSC-DSF
comment: Finds a process using a DB service and the associated service channel, plus the DB host and a copy of data served by the DB and flowing to it, but not from the process.

label: CDBSC-DST
comment: Finds a process using a DB service and the associated service channel, plus the DB host and a copy of data served by the DB and flowing from it, but not to the process.

label: CRoS
comment: Finds a Service and its Host, a Client Channel from a legitimate Client and its Host,  and a Logical Subnet used by at least one path from the client, plus the Client Path for that Client from this Subnet, and optionally the service manager and client user.

label: CRoSG
comment: Finds a Service and its Host, a Client Channel from a legitimate Client and its Host,  an Interface from a subnet to a Gateway host on at least one path from the Client, plus the Client Path from that subnet, and an access context for the gateway where it is on the relevant path, plus all service channels that relate to the client path, and optionally the service host manager and client user.

label: CRoSI
comment: Finds a Service and its Host, a Client Channel from a legitimate Client and its Host,  an Interface to a subnet on at least one path from the Client, and the Client Path from that Interface, and optionally the service manager and client user.

label: CSAPNaS
comment: Finds a host running a service, a closed service attack path to the service from a logical subnet, the location access contexts where the service is accessible via this attack path, and optionally the managers of the service and its host.

label: CSCCAPNP4
comment: Finds a service channel from a client to a service with a network path from an attacker subnet into the channel via a closed subnet, where the network path is consistent with an extension of the on-channel subpath.

label: CSCCHuoSt
comment: Finds a Human manager of a Service and a Client Channel to the Service from a Client, where the Client is managed by someone else, plus optionally the employer of the Service manager.

label: CSCCHuSt
comment: Finds a Human manager of a Service and their employer, and a Client Channel to the Service from a Client not operated by the employer.

label: CSCCmCC
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a Client Channel between them having at least one associated Client Channel indicating access is via a proxy.

label: CSCCSC
comment: Finds a Client and Service with a Client Channel between them and a single associated Service Channel.

label: CSCC-SC
comment: Finds a Client and Service running on different hosts with a ClientChannel but no ServiceChannel or ServiceProxy between them.

label: CSCLS
comment: Finds a client and its host and a service channel to the service via a logical subnet to which the host is connected, plus the associated network context.

label: CSCLS+ii
comment: Finds a client and its host and a service channel to the service via the Internet to which the host need not be connected, accessible from the World in which the host need not be located.

label: CSCLS-ii
comment: Finds a client and its host and a service channel to the service via a logical subnet (not a HostLAN or the Internet) to which the host need not be connected, accessible from a space in which the host need not be located.

label: CScP-v
comment: Finds a client directly or indirectly accessing a service which is controlled by another process, where the three processes are not in a credential forwarding or sharing chain and there is no link to say the cilent uses the third process for authentication.

label: CSCscLS
comment: Finds a Service Channel from a client process to a service, and a logical subnet from which source addresses are obscured by NAT.

label: CSCsdLS
comment: Finds a Service Channel from a client process to a service, and a logical subnet from which source addresses remain unaltered by NAT.

label: CSCvLS
comment: Finds a Service Channel from a client process to a service, and a logical subnet visited by it.

label: CSDS
comment: Finds a client and service plus the associated client channel where there is a data step from the client to the service.

label: CSHSAC
comment: Finds a service accessed by a client and an associated context for access to the service, plus the two process hosts and optionally the client user and service host manager.

label: CSL0H
comment: Finds a client channel whose client and service are collocated on a host that is not a cluster, and an internal (socket) LAN provided by the host accessible in a space.

label: CSL1H2
comment: Finds a client and service whose hosts are paired, plus their interfaces to the pair.

label: CSL3H
comment: Finds a client channel whose client and service are collocated on a cluster host that is accessible in a space, and an L3 Subnet connecting to the cluster.

label: CSLS2H2-SC
comment: Finds a client and service between which there is as yet no service channel, running on different hosts connected to different logical subnets that are not hotspots, connected by a network path in which neither host is a gateway.

label: CSLSH2-SC
comment: Finds a client and service on different hosts connected to the same network that is not a hotspot, and there is no existing service channel between them when the respective hosts are in locations where the network is accessible.

label: CS-SP
comment: Finds a client using a service not via a remote access service or a reverse proxy chain, where the client and service are both able to exchange data.

label: CucSaP
comment: Finds a Client using a Service as such (i.e., not via the host shell) using forwarded or shared credentials, and also using a third Process for authentication which controls the Service without being used by it.

label: CuPiS-i
comment: Finds a client process using a service indirectly using another service, where there is no link yet indictating that the client could communicate indirectly with the second service.

label: CuPnS-U
comment: Finds a client accessing a process that directly or indirectly uses a service, where the process shares or forwards client credentials and sends them to the service, and there is no link saying the client is sending shared credentials to the service.

label: CuPuSCC
comment: Finds a client accessing a service indirectly, via one intermediary which communicates directly with both, plus the auth channels between client and service and between each and the intermediary process.

label: CuPuS-i
comment: Finds a client process using a service using another service, where there is no link yet indictating that the client could communicate indirectly with the second service.

label: CuPvnS
comment: Finds a client accessing a process that is in a credential forwarding chain with a service used indirectly by the client (i.e., the service is at the end of the chain).

label: CuPvSCC
comment: Finds a client accessing a service indirectly, where there is more than one intermediary, plus the first intermediary adjacent to the client, and channels between client and service and between the client and this intermediary process.

label: CuScS
comment: Finds a client using a service for application or authentication and also controlled by the service.

label: CuSPvS-U
comment: Finds a client directly using a reverse proxy that uses a service, where the client has as yet no link indicating that the client is indirectly using the service.

label: CuvS
comment: Finds a client indirectly accessing a process via a credential sharing/forwarding chain.

label: CvPuSCC
comment: Finds a client accessing a service via more than one intermediary, plus the last intermediary adjacent to the service, and channels between client and service and between this intermediary process and the service.

label: CvPvSCC
comment: Finds a client accessing a service via at least two intermediaries, and two intermediaries that are adjacent, and the channels between client and service and between these two intermediary processes.

label: CzS-CC
comment: Finds a client providing authorization claims to a remote service, where there is no client channel linking the two.

label: CzSzP
comment: Finds a client sending an authorization token to a service which uses a separate OAuth-style process to validate and exchange the token.

label: DDoS
comment: Finds a service with which at least one client communicates via the Internet.

label: DFDSCS
comment: Finds a DataFlow via a DataStep that flows via a ClientChannel in the direction client to service.

label: DFDSfP
comment: Finds a DataFlow via a DataStep from a Process.

label: DFDSSC
comment: Finds a DataFlow via a DataStep that flows via a ClientChannel in the direction service to client.

label: DFfCCCfS
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the client where it can access the channel, plus a data flow over the channel from client to service.

label: DFfCCCtS
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the service where it can be accessed via the channel, plus a data flow over the channel from client to service.

label: DFrXSS
comment: Finds human using a web browser that uses a service with a host, where the browser receives from another process (not the service) data not created by either the browser or its user , plus the client channel between the browser and the service which must go via an IP subnet, and optionally the service and service host managers.

label: DFsXSS
comment: Finds a human using a web browser that accesses a service running on a Host and using inflowing data, along with optional host and service managers. The data flow destination is matched twice so it can be referred to in CSGs using different role names.

label: DFtCCCfS
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the client where it can access the channel, plus a data flow over the channel from service to client.

label: DFtCCCtS
comment: Finds a client-service channel, the client and service, and an access context at the service where it can be accessed via the channel, plus a data flow over the channel from service to client.

label: DFtP
comment: Finds a DataFlow to a Process.

label: DFuCuS-C-P
comment: Finds a data flow via two processes, one of which is indirectly a client of the other via a chain of credential sharing/forwarding intermediaries, and the Client has no other client in the same chain, and the service has no other service in the same chain.

label: DoS
comment: Finds a service with its host, and a service attack path to the service from a (possibly remote) subnet, and all the interfaces to which traffic would flow along this attack path.

label: DSrXSS
comment: Finds human using a web browser that uses a service with a host, where the browser also uses locally stored data not entered or updated by the user, along with optional host and service managers.

label: DSsXSS
comment: Finds a human using a web browser that accesses a service running on a host and using stored input data, along with optional host and service managers.

label: HLSISC
comment: Finds a host connecting to a logical subnet, by authenticating to a controlling service.

label: HPsACdDSCCV
comment: Finds a host running a Process with write/delete access (crudd) to a locally stored data copy, plus the data access asset representing the data deserialization, and a channel to a key vault that controls the stored data, plus any data fields included in the data copy and used by the process, the process access contexts (a non-unique sufficient match), and optionally the process host manager.

label: HPsACrDSCCV
comment: Finds a host running a Process with read access (crudr) to a locally stored data copy, plus the data access asset representing the data deserialization, and a channel to a key vault that controls the stored data, plus any data fields included in the data copy and used by the process, the process access contexts (a non-unique sufficient match), and optionally the process host manager.

label: H-sDFcCaiAC
comment: Finds a Process that creates data not stored on its host, which it sends to a service, and has a location access context where it can connect to the service but where access to the service may be interrupted.

label: H-sDFcCr-aAC
comment: Finds a Process that creates data in a context that is not stored on its host, and sends it to a service over a channel that cannot be accessed in this context.

label: H-sDFCFdS-ACau
comment: Finds a Process that receives a data flow not saved on its host from a service over one channel, and sends the same data in a data flow to a different service over a second channel, where the Process has no location context in which it can access the first service and access cannot be interrupted to the second service.

label: H-sDFrSACdDFiaS
comment: Finds a Process that receives a data flow not saved on its host from a client over one channel, and reads (needs) different data also not saved on its host in a data flow from a service over a second channel, plus an associated process location context in which the process can be accessed via the first channel but access to the service over the second may be interrupted.

label: H-sDFSACaiFS
comment: Finds a Process that receives a data flow not saved on its host from a client over one channel, and sends the same data in a data flow to a service over a second channel, plus an associated process location context in which the process can be accessed via the first channel but access to the service over the second may be interrupted.

label: H-sDFSFdC
comment: Finds a process that receives data over a channel from a client, and sends the data over a channel from a different client, plus the process host which does not store the data.

label: H-sDFuCudDFdS-ACau
comment: Finds a Process that reads (needs) data not saved on its host sent from a service over one channel, and reads (needs) different data not saved on its host from a different service over a second channel, plus the process host, where the Process has no location context in which it can access the first service and access cannot be interrupted to the second service.

label: H-sDFuSdC
comment: Finds a process that reads (needs) data sent over a channel from a client and not saved on its host, and a second channel to the process from a distinct client, plus the process host.

label: HuCAPmSC
comment: Finds a client attack path from a subnet, plus the associated client, service process, host and manager, with service channels via the client attack path.

label: HuCCC-nS
comment: Finds the User of an interactive Client using a Service not managed by the same user and not using a separate authenticator, with a Client Channel between them, plus the client and service hosts and optionally the service manager.

label: HuDFrXSS
comment: Finds human using a web browser that uses a service with a host and a host manager, where the browser receives from another process (not the service) data not created by either the browser or its user, plus the client channel between the browser and the service which must go via an IP subnet, and optionally the service manager.

label: HuDFsXSS
comment: Finds a human using a web browser that accesses a service which is using inflowing data and whose host has a manager, plus optionally the service manager.

label: HuDFTCS
comment: Finds a Human using a Web Browser that accesses via at least one IP subnet a Service that does not use a separate authenticator service, where the browser consumes a data flow viewed but not updated by the user, plus the data access and client channel assets associated with the data use and client-service commnication.

label: HuDSrXSS
comment: Finds human using a web browser that uses a service with a host and host manager, where the browser also uses locally stored data not entered nor updated by the user, plus optionally the service manager.

label: HuDSsXSS
comment: Finds a web browser accessing a service which is using stored input, plus the service host and manager.

label: HuDSTCS
comment: Finds a Human using a Web Browser that accesses via at least one IP subnet a Service that does not use a separate authenticator service, where the browser consumes a locally stored data input viewed but not updated by the user, plus the data access and client channel assets associated with the data use and client-service commnication.

label: HuHW2ACE
comment: Finds a Human using a web browser running on a host to access email, when the host is located in a space, plus the associated host location access context and process contexts in which access to the webmail service is possible using networks to which the host is connected when in that location.

label: HuiHCCC-nS
comment: Finds a Human using a Host to run a Process that is a Client of a Service, where the Client is authenticated by the Service.

label: HuiHrCCC-nS
comment: Finds a Human using a Host running a Remote Access Client used to access a Process that is a Client of a Service, where the Client is authenticated by the Service.

label: HuirRACSPH
comment: Finds a Human interacting remotely with a Process via a Remote Access Clent, plus the Process Host, collocated Remote Access Service, and the Client Channel between the Remote Access Client and the Remote Access Service.

label: HuiSP
comment: Finds a Human interactively using a reverse proxy (which is not normally permitted).

label: HumCCC-nS
comment: Finds a User managing a Client that uses and authenticates directly with a Service, plus the ClientChannel between them, their hosts, and optionally the service and service host managers.

label: HuoStCCCS
comment: Finds a User of an interactive Client (not a transparent proxy) using a Service they do not manage, plus the ClientChannel and Client and Service hosts, and optionally the employer of the user and manager of the service.

label: HuRACP
comment: Finds a human interacting with a remote access client on a local host that is remotely using a process that is not a proxy.

label: HuSAPmSC
comment: Finds a service attack path from a subnet, plus the associated service process, host and manager, with service channels via the attack path.

label: HuSC
comment: Finds a service channel representing a privileged communication path to a service, plus the associated service process and service host, and the service and service host managers.

label: HuStCCCS
comment: Finds a User of an interactive Client using a Service they do not manage, plus the ClientChannel and Client and Service hosts, the employer of the user and optionally the manager of the service.

label: IDFfCCCftS-s
comment: Finds a client-service channel to a service, and a location context at the service where it can be accessed via the channel, plus a data flow over the channel from client to service which flows to the service in that context, is used as input and not stored on the service host.

label: ImSCf
comment: Finds an interface between a host and a logical subnet where at least one service channel goes from that interface.

label: LnSc-uP
comment: Finds a Remote Access Service controlling access to a process that does not use the service.

label: LnSucP-pS
comment: Finds a remote access service using a process to which it forwards credentials, where that process does not need those credentials to access another service.

label: LSmSC
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet and all service channels via that subnet.

label: NP1CCAPSC
comment: Finds a service channel via a closed subnet (before a subsequent NAT gateway) and a network path into the channel via this subnet traversing an unblocked logical segment from a subnet not in the service channel.

label: NP2CCAPSC
comment: Finds a service channel via a closed subnet (before a subsequent NAT gateway) with a nework path to the channel via this subnet, and an extension via an unblocked logical segment from a subnet not in the service channel.

label: NPSCCAP
comment: Finds an off-channel Client Attack Path via Network Path into a Service Channel.

label: OCAPNaS
comment: Finds a service and its host accessed by a client via the associated client channel on an open client attack path from a logical subnet where messages from the attacker can be distinguished from those from the client, plus all the associated service process contexts and interfaces from which client messages come, and optionally the client user and the service and service host managers.

label: OSAPLaS
comment: Finds a host connected to an L2 subnet running a service, an open service attack path from the subnet to the service, plus all location access contexts in which the service is accessible via this path, and optionally the managers of the service and its host.

label: OSAPNaS
comment: Finds a host running a service, an open service attack path to the service from a logical subnet, the location access contexts where the service is accessible via this attack path, and optionally the managers of the service and its host.

label: PCaFCSCCC
comment: Finds a client channel via a service channel which is accessible to a client in a process context.

label: PCaTSSCAP
comment: Finds an attack path path via a service channel on which a service is accessible in a process context.

label: PCaTSSCCC
comment: Finds a client channel via a service channel which gives access to a service in a process context.

label: PccCuS
comment: Finds a client using a service for application or authentication, not via a remote access service, where both client and service are controlled by the same process.

label: PCCPCCS-i
comment: Finds a reverse proxy accessing another reverse proxy that uses a service, via the associated client channels, and optionally the second reverse proxy manager, where there is no credential sharing between the reverse proxies and back-end service.

label: PcHpmS
comment: Finds a Process in the role of transparent Proxy to at least one Service, and controlling a Host.

label: PcLSpmS
comment: Finds a Process in the role of transparent Proxy to at least one Service, and controlling a Logical Subnet.

label: Pc-pPpmS
comment: Finds a Process in the role of transparent Proxy for at least one Service, controlling another Process (not one of those Services).

label: Pc-uCucmS
comment: Finds a process controlling but not receiving forwarded credentials from a client that is forwarding credentials to other back-end services.

label: PDFFA
comment: Finds a Data Flow, its source and destination processes, a related data use element at the source, and optionally the two process managers.

label: PILSsSC
comment: Finds a Process running on a Host connected via an Interface to a Logical Subnet, where the Process acts as a Service to at least one client communicating over that Interface, any of which is sufficient to cause a threat.

label: PnPnS-U
comment: Finds a client using a service with shared or forwarded credentials, where the service uses another service in the same way, and there is no link yet indicating that the client and the second service are in a credential sharing chain.

label: Pu-pPucmS
comment: Finds a client that forwards credentials to at least one service, and uses another process as a service without doing the same.

label: RACvSPHRASP-iPL
comment: Finds a host running a process that is not a reverse proxy or a remote access service, and a remote access service that uses the process, and is used via a reverse proxy chain by a remote access client.

label: RDvSPDtS
comment: Finds a remote desktop client using a reverse proxy chain that provides access to a remote desktop service.

label: RDvSPHP-iPL-RAS
comment: Finds a Host running a Process that is neither a remote access service nor a reverse proxy, but is used remotely via a reverse proxy chain by a Remote Desktop client, not mediated by a collocated remote access service.

label: RDvSPIP
comment: Finds a remote desktop client using a reverse proxy chain that provides access to an interactive process.

label: RTvSPCP
comment: Finds a remote terminal client using a reverse proxy chain that provides access to a console (command line interactive) process.

label: RTvSPHP-iPL-RAS
comment: Finds a Host running a Process that is neither a remote access service nor a reverse proxy, but is used via a reverse proxy chain by a Remote Terminal client, not mediated by a collocated remote access service.

label: RTvSPRAS
comment: Finds a remote terminal client using a reverse proxy chain that provides access to a remote access service.

label: SC
comment: Finds a client and service connected by a service channel, and optionally the service manager.

label: SCAPvLS
comment: Finds a Host running a Service connected to a Subnet visited by a Service Channel via an Attack Path to the Service Process.

label: SCCAP
comment: Finds a service channel linked with a closed client attack path from a logical subnet to the service process.

label: SCCHNPLS-lI
comment: Finds a Service Channel via a Logical Path from a Client, the Client Host, Subnet and Interface, where the Service Channel has no last interface.

label: ScDACDACCDF-c
comment: Finds a data flow to a service from an indirect client, where the client creates the data flow from an inbound data asset controlled by a vault, which does not control the outbound data flow.

label: ScDASDACCDF-c
comment: Finds a data flow from a service requested by an indirect client, where the service creates the data flow by decrypting an inbound data asset controlled by a vault, which does not control the outbound data flow.

label: SCDS
comment: Finds a client and service plus the associated client channel where there is a data step from the service to the client.

label: SCLPLSg
comment: Finds a service channel via a logical path that traverses a logical segment, plus the interfaces used by the segment.

label: SCLPvLS
comment: Finds a service channel via a logical path that visits a subnet.

label: SCLSg
comment: Finds a service channel that traverses a logical segment, along with the inbound and outbound interfaces to the segment host.

label: SCLSgfTS
comment: Finds a Service Channel traversing a NAT segment (with its interfaces) after which source addresses can be distinguished from a client.

label: SCLSgvTS-vS
comment: Finds a service channel traversing a logical segment, where the subnet after the segment has source addresses that cannot be distinguished from a client source address, and this has not yet been inferred for the subnet before the segment.

label: SCmCAP
comment: Finds a client and service connected by a service channel plus all associated client attack paths from subnets in the channel.

label: SCmCP
comment: Finds a client and service connected by a service channel, plus all client paths associated with that service channel.

label: SCmSg
comment: Finds a Service Channel traversing at least one logical segment, plus its Client and Service, and network interfaces.

label: SCNP2CPtI
comment: Finds a service channel via a client path from a subnet in the channel to an interface on a subnet at or after the start of the client path.

label: SCNSg
comment: Finds a Service Channel traversing a NAT segment, and the subnets on either side.

label: SCpSg
comment: Finds a Service Channel that traverses no logical segments, plus its Client and Service, and network interfaces.

label: SCsAPtI
comment: Finds an Attack Path from a subnet at the start of a Service Channel, the path from which is a subpath of the Service Channel path, a gateway segment visited along that path, and the subnet and interface on the attacker side of that gateway.

label: SCvLS-vS
comment: Finds a Service Channel that visits a Logical Subnet, with no relationship indicating that source addresses cannot be distinguished from a client.

label: SCxAPtI
comment: Finds an Attack Path starting from a subnet in a Service Channel, the path from which is a subpath of the Service Channel path, a gateway segment visited along that path, and the subnet and interface on the attacker side of that gateway.

label: SgACmSC
comment: Finds a logical segment between two subnets, plus the associated gateway host and its inbound and outbound interfaces, an access context in which the segment is active, and all assocated service channels.

label: SgmSC
comment: Finds a logical segment between two subnets, plus the associated gateway host and its inbound and outbound interfaces, and all assocated service channels.

label: SOCAP
comment: Finds a service channel linked with an open client attack path from a logical subnet to the service process, where there is no closed service attack path to the service from the same logical subnet.

label: SP
comment: Finds a reverse proxy process.

label: SPNaLnS
comment: Finds a host running a remote access service accessed by a reverse proxy, plus the associated client channel, the location and network contexts in which this can happen, and optionally the managers of the client proxy, service and service host.

label: SPNaS
comment: Finds a host running a service accessed via a reverse proxy, plus the associated client channel, contexts in which the service can be accessed, and optionally the managers of the client proxy, service and service host.

label: SPuS
comment: Finds a reverse proxy directly using a service.

label: SPvSPvS-U
comment: Finds a reverse proxy using a second reverse proxy that uses a service, with mutual authentication at each step, and with no link indicating that the first proxy may indirectly use the service.

label: SSClIAP
comment: Finds a service channel from a last interface to a service process via an attack path.

label: SSCLS
comment: Finds a service and its host and a service channel from a client via a logical subnet to which the host is connected, plus the associated network context.

label: A
comment: Finds a solo Adult.

label: CCSCHC
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that depends on connectivity represented by a Host Channel.

label: CCSCVC
comment: Finds a Client Channel via a Service Channel that requires connectivity represented by a Virtual Channel.

label: CVHHDC
comment: Finds a clusterable virtual Host provisioned on a physical host at a DataCentre.

label: CVHHHoDC
comment: Finds a cluster Virtual Host (role Host) provisioned at a Host (SHost), where the Virtual Host may optionally be managed by a Data Centre.

label: DCCVH-LS
comment: Finds a Data Centre with a Cluster on which is provisioned a Virtual Host that is not connected to any logical subnet.

label: DCVHVS-H
comment: Finds a Host that is physically in a DataCentre and connected to a virtual subnet that is not provided by any host.

label: EH
comment: Finds a solo elastically scalable host.

label: GdHVS
comment: Finds a gateway providing a virtual subnet to which a distinct host is connected, and optionally a process controlling access to the subnet.

label: H2dPH2
comment: Finds two hosts on a virtual subnet with distinct physical hosts, between which the virtualised communication must flow.

label: HACVHmAC
comment: Finds a host in a space provisioning a virtual host, and a location access context for the first host, plus all related access contexts for the virtual host.

label: HCLPLSg
comment: Finds a host channel via a logical path that traverses a logical segment.

label: HCLPvLS
comment: Finds a host channel via a logical path that visits a subnet.

label: HCLSg
comment: Finds a host channel that traverses a logical segment, along with the inbound and outbound interfaces to the segment host.

label: HL
comment: Finds a solo HostLAN

label: HuiVH
comment: Finds a Human interacting with a Virtual Host (which is not possible).

label: HumHVH-Hu
comment: Finds an unmanaged VirtualHost provisioned at a Host managed by a Human.

label: HVH
comment: Finds a VirtualHost and its host, and optionally its manager.

label: HVH-a
comment: Finds a VirtualHost provisioned at a Host where the pair lacks the above relationship indicating which is higher.

label: HVHS
comment: Finds a VirtualHost provisioned at a Host that is not a cluster and is located in a physical Space.

label: HVSICSG
comment: Finds a host connecting to a virtual subnet that it does not provide, plus the controlling service and connection to it from the authentication client on the host.

label: ImHCf
comment: Finds an interface between a host and a logical subnet where at least one host channel goes from that interface.

label: ImHCt
comment: Finds an interface between a host and a logical subnet where at least one host channel goes to that interface.

label: INCmHCf
comment: Finds an Interface, plus the associated host, subnet, and a host network access context where the interface is connected, plus all host channels from the interface.

label: INCmHCt
comment: Finds an Interface, plus the associated host, subnet, and a host network access context where the interface is connected, plus all host channels to the interface.

label: LSmHC
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet and all virtualised host channels via that subnet.

label: LSoLS
comment: Finds a Logical Subnet that is an overlay on another Subnet.

label: mLSoLS
comment: Finds a solo Logical Subnet which is an overlay of at least one other subnet.

label: pLSoLS
comment: Finds a solo Overlay Subnet lacking any other subnet on which it is an overlay.

label: SC4HVSHC
comment: Finds a Service Channel crossing a Virtual Subnet between two Hosts, and the Host Channel representing a physical network path supporting this communication.

label: SC4HVSVC
comment: Finds a Service Channel crossing a Virtual Subnet between two Hosts, and the Virtual Channel representing the physical connectivity requirement to support this communication.

label: SgACmHC
comment: Finds a logical segment between two subnets, plus the associated gateway host and its inbound and outbound interfaces, an access context in which the segment is active, and all assocated host channels.

label: SgmHC
comment: Finds a logical segment between two subnets, plus the associated gateway host and its inbound and outbound interfaces, and all assocated host channels.

label: THVH
comment: Finds a Virtual Host provisioned on a Trivial Host.

label: VC2HmHC
comment: Finds a virtual channel between two physical hosts, plus all the host channels associated with physical network paths between the hosts.

label: VC2HmSC
comment: Finds a virtual channel between two physical hosts, plus all the service channels associated with physical network paths between the hosts.

label: VCH2LS2PP
comment: Finds a virtual subnet communication path between physical hosts, including the virtual channel, path generator and the start and end subnets.

label: VH2H-a
comment: Finds three virtual hosts in a chain but lacking the above relationship indicating which of the first and last links is higher.

label: VHH2
comment: Finds a VirtualHost provisioned at a Host for which it is also on the path to a physical host.

label: VHH3
comment: Finds a virtual host provisioned by two distinct hosts.

label: VHHHoDC
comment: Finds a Virtual Host (role Host) provisioned at a Host (SHost), where the Virtual Host may optionally be provisioned by a Data Centre.

label: VHHsD-HsS-S
comment: Finds a Virtual Host above another Host in a virtualisation stack where both store the same Data, there is no lower level host in the stack that also stores the data, and the second host does not run a Process that serves the Data.

label: VHPH
comment: Finds a virtual host provisioned by a physical host.

label: VHPhDHS-HsS-S
comment: Finds a Virtual Host running a Process that handles Data but does not access it via a service, where its host is in a virtualisation stack above a second Host running a service for the Data, and there is no host between the two in the virtualisation stack running a Process that Serves the Data.

label: VSHCmSC
comment: Finds a host channel supporting a virtual subnet, and the associated hosts, along with all service channels that use the host channel.

label: VSPSH
comment: Finds a Virtual Subnet provided by a gateway host using a Physical Subnet to route at least one host-host connection, and optionally the process controlling the virtual subnet, and the manager of the gateway.

label: VSPS-HP
comment: Finds a Virtual Subnet using a Physical Subnet to route at least one host-host connection, where there is no gateway specified as the subnet provider, and no controlling Process.

label: VSPSH-P
comment: Finds a Virtual Subnet with no controlling Process, provided by a gateway host using a Physical Subnet to route at least one host-host connection, and optionally the manager of the Gateway.

label: VSVC4H-PP
comment: Finds a virtual subnet and two connected hosts with distinct physical hosts between which virtual subnet messages should flow, and yet there is no host channel, indicating no physical path between the physical hosts was found.

label: VSVCHC
comment: Finds a Virtual Subnet via a Virtual Channel via a Host Channel.

label: VSVCHCLS
comment: Finds a virtual subnet that uses a physical subnet.
